This is dangerous enough.

43
00:07:28,982 --> 00:07:34,637
If this man's brain temp goes one C above 43, he's a veg.

44
00:07:39,560 --> 00:07:41,750
Come on, Mike.

45
00:07:52,539 --> 00:07:53,864
Here we go.

46
00:08:05,152 --> 00:08:07,103
It's all clean.

47
00:08:10,991 --> 00:08:13,749
Good morning, sunshine.

48
00:08:14,128 --> 00:08:16,318
Hey, how you doing, big guy?

49
00:08:16,530 --> 00:08:17,752
- OK?
- Yeah.

50
00:08:17,965 --> 00:08:19,825
All right. Thank you. Take it easy.

51
00:08:19,833 --> 00:08:23,394
Slow, slow, slow.
There's no hurry, OK?

52
00:08:24,471 --> 00:08:27,992
- That's it. Good?
- Yeah.

53
00:08:28,208 --> 00:08:30,830
Good man. Hey, Mike, look at me.

54
00:08:31,044 --> 00:08:33,097
Look at me. Right here.

55
00:08:33,981 --> 00:08:36,432
What's the last date you remember?

56
00:08:37,651 --> 00:08:40,445
- October 19.
- Very good.

57
00:08:41,789 --> 00:08:44,417
Mike, what's the last thing you remember?

58
00:08:48,262 --> 00:08:49,917
The Red Sox made the playoffs.

59
00:08:51,098 --> 00:08:55,126
OK. Let's get the legal out of the way, shall we?

60
00:08:55,569 --> 00:09:00,037
Mr. Michael Jennings,
under the terms of your non-disclosure agreement,...

61
00:09:00,040 --> 00:09:03,126
...you are considered never to have been an employee.

62
00:09:03,143 --> 00:09:08,434
You also understand that all your work
is the intellectual property of Nexim...

63
00:09:08,449 --> 00:09:10,502
Yeah. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

64
00:09:10,718 --> 00:09:14,575
I never worked here. I never saw anybody.
I never was here. I got it.

65
00:09:14,588 --> 00:09:16,573
Is my paycheck ready?

66
00:09:24,531 --> 00:09:26,622
Alrighty.

67
00:09:26,700 --> 00:09:29,395
- How you feeling, tiger?
- Good.

68
00:09:29,403 --> 00:09:31,991
- Now let's hear you.
- All right.

69
00:09:32,206 --> 00:09:34,726
- Ready?
- Yeah.

70
00:09:35,676 --> 00:09:36,901
Go!

71
00:09:41,548 --> 00:09:45,644
In order to zero the full eight weeks
I had to heat your brain to 42.5 C.

72
00:09:45,652 --> 00:09:49,009
- I'm fine.
- I'm saying it's getting harder, Mike.

73
00:09:49,023 --> 00:09:52,152
- I said, I'm fine.
- You're slowing down actually. Come on.

74
00:09:52,159 --> 00:09:53,848
I'd be faster if you'd shut up.

75
00:09:54,061 --> 00:09:56,182
Show me what you've got, grasshopper.

76
00:09:57,564 --> 00:09:59,492
That's it. That's more like it!

77
00:10:00,034 --> 00:10:03,691
Yes! Go, go, go!

78
00:10:03,904 --> 00:10:05,491
Go! Go!

79
00:10:06,707 --> 00:10:08,692
Yes! Faster!

80
00:10:10,978 --> 00:10:13,168
Beautiful!

81
00:10:13,580 --> 00:10:16,839
Yes! One more! One more, Mikey!

82
00:10:19,453 --> 00:10:21,981
Now you see how you did that?
How you focused?

83
00:10:21,989 --> 00:10:25,443
- Yeah, I focus on your face.
- Oh, no. You know you Iove me.

84
00:10:25,444 --> 00:10:29,082
Come on. Come on.
Don't be mean to the one who does everything for you.

85
00:10:29,229 --> 00:10:34,487
Do you realize you've never once
asked me what I see when I erase your memory?

86
00:10:34,701 --> 00:10:38,126
Basically, the last two months just never happened for you.

87
00:10:38,338 --> 00:10:40,932
What's to know?
20 hours a day in a clean room...

88
00:10:40,941 --> 00:10:44,798
...ripping off one guy's idea for a computer,
selling it to somebody else. You know.

89
00:10:44,812 --> 00:10:46,740
What'd you do the last two months?

90
00:10:46,947 --> 00:10:50,736
You know, the last thing I remember is
driving in Spain in the Aston Martin,...

91
00:10:50,751 --> 00:10:54,403
...learning to dive in Belize with what's-her-name.

92
00:10:54,421 --> 00:10:57,277
The seven-stadiums-in-seven-days trip.
It's great.

93
00:10:57,291 --> 00:11:01,012
I mean, my memories are basically highlights.

94
00:11:01,028 --> 00:11:05,488
It's good. It's a good life.
The stuff you erase, it doesn't matter.

95
00:12:10,898 --> 00:12:12,792
What is it with guys like Rethrick?

96
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:15,228
- He's gotta have everything, huh?
- Well,...

97
00:12:15,502 --> 00:12:19,496
...say what you want about Jimmy,
he started Allcom in his garage.

98
00:12:42,930 --> 00:12:48,481
- Wait, wait. Don't you leave me alone.
- What? You'll be fine. Talk. Mingle.

99
00:12:51,438 --> 00:12:53,832
I don't want to mingle.

100
00:12:58,178 --> 00:12:59,662
Hello.

101
00:13:04,585 --> 00:13:08,306
- I'm Michael.
- I'm Rachel.

102
00:13:09,089 --> 00:13:10,482
Rachel Porter.

103
00:13:10,691 --> 00:13:13,211
Is that Miss or Mrs?

104
00:13:15,362 --> 00:13:21,460
- That would be Dr. Porter.
- Doctor. Well, excuse me, doctor.

105
00:13:21,468 --> 00:13:22,793
It's all right.

106
00:13:23,003 --> 00:13:25,830
What kind of a doctor are you?

107
00:13:26,040 --> 00:13:28,059
- I'm a biologist.
- Really?

108
00:13:33,080 --> 00:13:35,065
Do you work for Jimmy?

109
00:13:35,282 --> 00:13:38,377
So it must be very top-secret biology that you practice.

110
00:13:38,652 --> 00:13:40,409
Oh, yes. Isn't everything?

111
00:13:46,794 --> 00:13:48,449
Let's go.

112
00:13:49,229 --> 00:13:50,554
Excuse me?

113
00:13:50,764 --> 00:13:55,361
I mean, I'm happy to continue blathering on,...

114
00:13:55,362 --> 00:13:57,161
...trying helplessly to charm you,...

115
00:13:57,204 --> 00:14:03,197
...but I thought maybe, you know,
cut to the chase and just, you know, go somewhere.

116
00:14:09,049 --> 00:14:10,840
I'll tell you what, Michael.

117
00:14:11,652 --> 00:14:14,781
I'm gonna walk over there and talk to a friend of mine.

118
00:14:15,422 --> 00:14:19,450
If you get the urge to have a real conversation,...

119
00:14:20,094 --> 00:14:21,749
...you'll know where to find me.

120
00:14:24,365 --> 00:14:26,816
OK. Fair enough.

121
00:14:27,101 --> 00:14:28,385
It was nice to meet you.

122
00:14:30,671 --> 00:14:33,065
Giving up so easily?

123
00:14:33,574 --> 00:14:36,965
You don't believe in second chances, now, do you?

124
00:14:37,545 --> 00:14:40,173
In my experience, no, I don't.

125
00:14:43,651 --> 00:14:46,341
- Good night.
- Good night.

126
00:14:52,793 --> 00:14:55,621
- Mike.
- Jimmy.

127
00:14:55,629 --> 00:14:56,849
- How you doing?
- Good. How you doing?

128
00:14:56,864 --> 00:14:58,089
- Good to see you.
- You too.

129
00:14:58,099 --> 00:14:59,828
- Thanks for coming.
- Thanks for having me.

130
00:14:59,834 --> 00:15:00,886
- Come back this way.
- Sure.

131
00:15:01,101 --> 00:15:03,393
Hey, Jimmy.

132
00:15:08,375 --> 00:15:11,463
Now you're talking. Thank you.

133
00:15:13,314 --> 00:15:14,798
Wait a second.

134
00:15:15,349 --> 00:15:18,507
Isaac, disable fire protection, please.

135
00:15:19,220 --> 00:15:20,942
Alarm disabled.

136
00:15:23,757 --> 00:15:27,580
I don't think you'd look so good covered in foam.
Even in that spiffy suit.

137
00:15:27,595 --> 00:15:29,284
What's the pitch, Jimmy?

138
00:15:29,496 --> 00:15:32,716
I've known you long enough to know when
you're trying to sell me something. What is it?

139
00:15:34,101 --> 00:15:39,165
When there was a time we were in school,
we wanted to change the world.

140
00:15:39,373 --> 00:15:42,804
I thought we said we wanted to save the world.
Well, that's semantics.

141
00:15:43,277 --> 00:15:45,701
- What's the job, Jimmy?
- Can't tell you.

142
00:15:46,180 --> 00:15:52,151
Other than to say that it involves optics.
And you get stock options for this one.

143
00:15:52,353 --> 00:15:54,713
Get a real piece of the company.

144
00:15:55,222 --> 00:15:58,943
What if it doesn't work?
I get a real piece of nothing.

145
00:15:58,959 --> 00:16:01,353
I promise you, it won't fail.

146
00:16:02,563 --> 00:16:05,624
How do you know that?
Is this a real crystal ball?

147
00:16:05,933 --> 00:16:10,259
I wish.
The point is, I'll guarantee that you do eight figures.

148
00:16:12,573 --> 00:16:15,702
- Minimum.
- What's the catch?

149
00:16:15,943 --> 00:16:19,504
The job may require a little bit more time than you're used to.

150
00:16:19,513 --> 00:16:22,733
- How much more time?
- Two years. Maybe three.

151
00:16:22,750 --> 00:16:24,878
- You're kidding.
- Deadly serious.

152
00:16:25,352 --> 00:16:28,076
Jimmy, that's impossible.
You can't do it.

153
00:16:28,078 --> 00:16:30,508
The longest anyone has ever done is eight weeks.
I know because it was me.

154
00:16:30,524 --> 00:16:33,346
Assuming it were possible, would you do it?

155
00:16:36,397 --> 00:16:39,492
- Give up three years of my life?
- Not give up, trade.

156
00:16:39,500 --> 00:16:42,424
Three years in return for the rest of your life.

157
00:16:42,803 --> 00:16:46,096
One big paycheck. You're done.

158
00:16:55,749 --> 00:16:57,609
A lot can happen in three years.

159
00:16:57,818 --> 00:17:00,342
You blink, it'll be over-- to you, it'll be two seconds.

160
00:17:00,344 --> 00:17:05,784
A heartbeat, then snap, you're rich beyond your wildest dreams.

161
00:17:05,793 --> 00:17:09,416
One big paycheck. You're done.

162
00:18:09,523 --> 00:18:12,350
Mr. Jennings. John Wolfe.
Welcome.

163
00:18:13,227 --> 00:18:16,015
You understand that you won't be allowed to leave the grounds.

164
00:18:16,030 --> 00:18:18,624
You'll be assigned a residence right here on campus.

165
00:18:18,632 --> 00:18:23,852
All your mail will be screened, no outside phone calls,
and anything you do receive will have to be inspected.

166
00:18:23,871 --> 00:18:25,093
Okay.

167
00:18:27,007 --> 00:18:28,958
I'm going to need all your personal belongings --...

168
00:18:29,176 --> 00:18:32,897
...watch, wallet, anything else you're carrying.
I'm afraid nothing's allowed to be brought in.

169
00:18:36,717 --> 00:18:40,438
All these items will be returned to you when you pick up your paycheck.

170
00:18:40,454 --> 00:18:41,847
Sorry. Those too.

171
00:18:47,861 --> 00:18:50,888
- Mike, hey, you made it.
- Yeah.

172
00:18:51,131 --> 00:18:52,781
- Good to see you.
- See you too.

173
00:18:52,800 --> 00:18:54,751
- Everything OK?
- Yep.

174
00:18:56,904 --> 00:18:58,126
Sit down.

175
00:18:58,339 --> 00:19:00,207
I assume Mr. Wolfe gave you all the fine print.

176
00:19:00,215 --> 00:19:05,337
Yeah. He also took the last pair of sunglasses
I've managed not to lose.

177
00:19:05,546 --> 00:19:07,406
I'm sorry.

178
00:19:13,921 --> 00:19:15,712
What is this?

179
00:19:16,257 --> 00:19:17,684
It's for your memory wipe.

180
00:19:17,892 --> 00:19:22,626
We inject you with an isotope,
migrates to your brain lodges, serves as a marker.

181
00:19:22,630 --> 00:19:25,588
Then, when we're done, another injection erases everything back to the marker.

182
00:19:25,733 --> 00:19:28,753
No barbaric cooking of the brain.

183
00:19:38,479 --> 00:19:40,066
All right.

184
00:20:03,203 --> 00:20:06,992
- What have I gotten myself into?
- Let's go find out.

185
00:20:14,882 --> 00:20:17,709
Initiating Blue Script directory.

186
00:20:21,488 --> 00:20:22,972
Impressive.

187
00:20:23,190 --> 00:20:27,079
This used to be our smallest unit.
Now it's our most profitable.

188
00:20:27,094 --> 00:20:30,089
Excuse me Mr. Rethrick, may I speak with you for a moment?

189
00:20:30,097 --> 00:20:32,748
- Have a look around. I'll be right back.
- OK.

190
00:20:35,903 --> 00:20:40,193
Cycle complete.
Begin transmission of data.

191
00:20:50,317 --> 00:20:52,604
All right! I give up! I give up.

192
00:21:11,472 --> 00:21:13,627
Don't give up.

193
00:21:15,543 --> 00:21:21,309
- Dr. Porter. I guess I'm lucky you didn't use thunder and lightning.
- True.

194
00:21:27,721 --> 00:21:32,617
OK, well, I won't question your powers in the future.

195
00:21:33,828 --> 00:21:36,382
Sorry, I just couldn't help myself.

196
00:21:36,597 --> 00:21:39,091
I thought you said Marianne was on a plane tonight.

197
00:21:39,099 --> 00:21:42,717
She was planning to make the
conference call from the plane, sir.

198
00:21:44,438 --> 00:21:49,135
Look. I should probably apologize for my behavior the other day.

199
00:21:49,143 --> 00:21:52,695
- I -- I get like that sometimes, and I shouldn't. I'm sorry.
- Careful.

200
00:21:52,713 --> 00:21:57,105
You are in danger of sounding like you want a second chance.

201
00:22:04,892 --> 00:22:08,015
- Everything okay?
- Yeah.

202
00:22:24,178 --> 00:22:27,236
- Say something else.
- Excuse me?

203
00:22:27,247 --> 00:22:30,140
Say something nice.
Quick, otherwise I'll forget it.

204
00:22:32,353 --> 00:22:34,679
Was that little breeze for our boy here?

205
00:22:34,922 --> 00:22:38,549
Well, I owed him one. Now we're even.

206
00:22:38,659 --> 00:22:41,253
Well, be nice 'cause Mike's moving into the neighborhood.

207
00:22:41,662 --> 00:22:43,180
Oh.

208
00:22:46,267 --> 00:22:49,025
- See you around.
- OK.

209
00:22:54,241 --> 00:22:57,602
- You ready?
- Yeah. Let's go.

210
00:23:00,614 --> 00:23:02,633
You can still back out.

211
00:23:04,251 --> 00:23:06,042
No hard feelings.

212
00:23:17,631 --> 00:23:20,116
No, I want to stay.

213
00:23:20,334 --> 00:23:24,521
Michael Jennings, meet the other half of your team, Dr. William Dekker.

214
00:23:29,310 --> 00:23:31,864
- Nice to meet you.
- It's a pleasure.

215
00:23:32,079 --> 00:23:36,036
Gentlemen.
Let's have a look at the next three years of your lives.

216
00:24:15,856 --> 00:24:17,340
What happened?

217
00:24:19,526 --> 00:24:21,044
Michael.

218
00:24:22,262 --> 00:24:23,917
You're done.

219
00:24:26,934 --> 00:24:31,087
- How long was it, Jimmy?
- It's been three years, Mike.

220
00:24:32,506 --> 00:24:35,765
- How'd I do?
- You did good.

221
00:24:37,177 --> 00:24:40,704
Your money's been transferred to your account at Reddy Grant & Associates.

222
00:24:40,714 --> 00:24:42,767
You've got an appointment there today at 1:00.

223
00:24:42,983 --> 00:24:46,913
Just go home, do the paperwork.
When you feel up to it, give me a call.

224
00:24:46,954 --> 00:24:48,905
We've got a lot of catching up to do Mike.

225
00:25:05,072 --> 00:25:07,523
Ninety-two million dollars.

226
00:25:33,467 --> 00:25:36,131
Everyone at Reddy Grant associates appreciates your business sir.

227
00:25:36,133 --> 00:25:40,556
Well, not as much as I appreciate my business, I promise you.

228
00:25:41,375 --> 00:25:43,303
OK.

229
00:25:45,546 --> 00:25:47,474
Just sign there.

230
00:25:52,019 --> 00:25:54,140
- All right.
- Great.

231
00:25:54,354 --> 00:25:56,680
- Your personal items.
- Yes.

232
00:25:56,890 --> 00:25:58,442
You only needed four stamps.

233
00:26:01,528 --> 00:26:05,089
Oh, well, guess I could afford the extra 50 cents.

234
00:26:14,007 --> 00:26:16,697
I don't think this is my stuff.

235
00:26:16,910 --> 00:26:18,497
- It's not?
- No.

236
00:26:19,880 --> 00:26:23,936
- I-I-I don't know what happened.
- It's all right. Don't worry about it.

237
00:26:23,984 --> 00:26:26,874
It doesn't matter.
Let's talk about my shares.

238
00:26:27,421 --> 00:26:31,842
What I'd like to do is get some money now,...

239
00:26:31,859 --> 00:26:37,124
...and, you know, put the rest away for long term, you know, to live off.
So how do we -- So how do we do that?

240
00:26:38,299 --> 00:26:41,393
Mr. Jennings, you forfeited your shares.

241
00:26:43,937 --> 00:26:45,496
I beg your pardon? What?

242
00:26:45,806 --> 00:26:52,035
Yeah, here. Dated four weeks ago.

