00:49:39,513 --> 00:49:45,016
Each item has to be used at a specific time, at a specific
place to accomplish whatever it was I needed to get done.

483
00:49:45,019 --> 00:49:48,444
I mean, without the stuff in here,
I'd already be dead.

484
00:49:48,455 --> 00:49:52,915
Yeah, well, it's too bad that you don't
know what the rest of them are for.

485
00:49:56,764 --> 00:49:58,555
What?

486
00:50:18,352 --> 00:50:20,246
Gotcha!

487
00:50:29,596 --> 00:50:30,989
Hey!

488
00:50:33,233 --> 00:50:35,285
Great seeing you again, Mike!

489
00:50:36,003 --> 00:50:37,658
Jesus!

490
00:50:54,088 --> 00:50:56,448
Those guys do not look like feds.

491
00:50:58,025 --> 00:51:00,613
Here. Listen to me.
Take this.

492
00:51:00,828 --> 00:51:04,856
This will get you through that door.
Close it behind you. Understand? Go!

493
00:51:04,865 --> 00:51:07,555
- OK!
- Go! Go on!

494
00:51:11,705 --> 00:51:12,962
Shit!

495
00:51:14,475 --> 00:51:15,959
Go!

496
00:51:40,401 --> 00:51:43,792
Oh, God, I hope that was a good thing to do.

497
00:53:13,393 --> 00:53:14,786
Shit.

498
00:54:17,791 --> 00:54:19,309
Go.

499
00:54:20,594 --> 00:54:22,115
Where's your gun?

500
00:54:22,829 --> 00:54:24,279
He's got it.

501
00:54:35,809 --> 00:54:39,031
So how are you, Mike?

502
00:54:41,715 --> 00:54:43,199
You?

503
00:54:44,218 --> 00:54:45,645
Why?

504
00:54:46,553 --> 00:54:48,242
Don't remember?

505
00:54:49,056 --> 00:54:51,917
You brought this on yourself, Mike.

506
00:54:57,664 --> 00:55:02,683
So how does it feel knowing you're going to die?

507
00:56:24,818 --> 00:56:26,109
Shit.

508
00:57:07,261 --> 00:57:12,856
- So you are saying he designed his own escape?
- Mr. Attorney General, sir, we have no explanation.

509
00:57:12,866 --> 00:57:17,694
Because after looking at all the evidence the only logical,
albeit hard-to-accept conclusion,...

510
00:57:17,705 --> 00:57:21,028
...is that he was able to predict what was going to happen to him.

511
00:57:21,275 --> 00:57:24,529
These are memories extracted from Jennings before he fled.

512
00:57:24,545 --> 00:57:27,269
They don't seem to add up to anything.

513
00:57:29,516 --> 00:57:31,341
Gladys.

514
00:57:32,853 --> 00:57:34,838
That's all for today.

515
00:57:41,128 --> 00:57:43,756
We knew Dekker was trying to design something,...

516
00:57:43,764 --> 00:57:47,121
...but when he sold his plans, he wasn't even halfway done.

517
00:57:47,134 --> 00:57:48,356
I don't understand.

518
00:57:48,569 --> 00:57:51,994
Dekker was working at JPL on a laser-enhanced lens.

519
00:57:52,039 --> 00:57:56,858
He claimed the lens was powerful
enough to see around the curvature of the universe.

520
00:57:57,111 --> 00:58:00,672
...Dekker believed that if you could see
around a curve that went on forever...

521
00:58:00,681 --> 00:58:04,511
...you would end up back where you started, looking at yourself.

522
00:58:04,718 --> 00:58:08,043
Except you're not looking back at yourself now, in the present.

523
00:58:08,045 --> 00:58:11,409
No, you are not.
You're looking at the future.

524
00:58:11,992 --> 00:58:16,452
Can you imagine what'll happen if Jennings figures out what he's done,
and tries to profit from it?

525
00:58:16,463 --> 00:58:19,786
- Any nation in the world would give him a king's ransom.
- Jennings won't do that.

526
00:58:19,800 --> 00:58:21,665
I was this close to him. He never lied.

527
00:58:21,668 --> 00:58:24,192
When he heard what he's being accused of, he was hurt and scared.

528
00:58:24,194 --> 00:58:26,789
Fine, once you bring him in I'll give him the Medal of Honor.

529
00:58:26,807 --> 00:58:29,561
That's if Rethrick doesn't find him first.

530
00:58:35,482 --> 00:58:37,706
You think he really saw the future?

531
00:58:39,620 --> 00:58:41,241
That would be something.

532
00:59:53,160 --> 00:59:54,417
Café Michel?

533
00:59:54,628 --> 00:59:56,486
My name is Michael Jennings.

534
00:59:56,498 --> 01:00:01,922
And I can't remember if I made a reservation there recently.

535
01:00:01,925 --> 01:00:05,128
Would you check that out for me?
Thanks.

536
01:00:06,407 --> 01:00:08,198
I did?

537
01:00:09,243 --> 01:00:10,693
OK.

538
01:00:10,911 --> 01:00:13,271
Right. How many is it for?

539
01:00:15,616 --> 01:00:18,943
Oh, no, thank you.
No, I'll be there.

540
01:00:19,153 --> 01:00:20,740
Thank you.

541
01:00:41,442 --> 01:00:43,165
Hello, you two.

542
01:00:46,013 --> 01:00:48,032
Did he feed you?

543
01:01:10,804 --> 01:01:12,129
Rachel, it's Jimmy.

544
01:01:14,108 --> 01:01:17,299
- You all right?
- Why?

545
01:01:18,812 --> 01:01:20,034
You don't know?

546
01:01:21,682 --> 01:01:23,007
No.

547
01:01:24,651 --> 01:01:25,942
May I come in?

548
01:01:27,321 --> 01:01:29,613
When was the last time you saw Michael?

549
01:01:29,823 --> 01:01:31,910
Yesterday morning.

550
01:01:32,126 --> 01:01:35,619
He was pulling an all nighter at his lab.

551
01:01:38,932 --> 01:01:42,220
Rachel, I'm sorry to have to be the one to tell you this.

552
01:01:42,469 --> 01:01:46,497
Michael left Allcom yesterday.
Permanently.

553
01:01:49,076 --> 01:01:51,971
- What?
- He finished his work.

554
01:01:53,313 --> 01:01:56,003
- We erased his memory, and he--
- No.

555
01:01:56,216 --> 01:01:59,577
- He left.
- No. He promised me.

556
01:01:59,787 --> 01:02:02,745
He said he wasn't going to go through with it.

557
01:02:02,756 --> 01:02:05,407
He made a lot of money on this one, Rachel.

558
01:02:06,493 --> 01:02:09,149
He said he didn't care about the money.

559
01:02:19,106 --> 01:02:21,000
So she doesn't know anything.

560
01:02:21,208 --> 01:02:22,829
He wouldn't leave without her.

561
01:02:23,043 --> 01:02:24,698
It's Michael. He'd be smart.

562
01:02:27,181 --> 01:02:29,041
We're missing something.

563
01:02:57,578 --> 01:03:00,036
As soon as she leaves for work, get in there.

564
01:03:00,047 --> 01:03:01,998
And make sure she can't go anywhere alone.

565
01:03:03,250 --> 01:03:05,804
I want to know what just happened.

566
01:03:13,193 --> 01:03:15,246
Bye, guys.

567
01:03:20,234 --> 01:03:22,628
Good morning, Dr. Porter.

568
01:03:25,973 --> 01:03:27,597
Going somewhere?

569
01:03:36,884 --> 01:03:38,402
Good morning.

570
01:03:42,489 --> 01:03:44,041
Good morning.

571
01:03:52,099 --> 01:03:54,220
I'm going to go up top.
Take my bag.

572
01:03:55,970 --> 01:03:58,655
- You're gonna need this.
- Got it. Thanks.

573
01:04:04,912 --> 01:04:06,362
Coming?

574
01:04:06,580 --> 01:04:09,240
No, thanks.
I'd rather watch from down here.

575
01:04:09,250 --> 01:04:10,873
Suit yourself.

576
01:04:19,293 --> 01:04:24,288
Look, we've been through the bathroom and
tossed the rest of the apartment, too. Zero.

577
01:04:24,298 --> 01:04:27,484
This is what I want you to do.
Go back in the bathroom.

578
01:04:39,914 --> 01:04:42,809
OK, start turning left.

579
01:04:44,952 --> 01:04:46,846
Tell me what you see.

580
01:04:47,988 --> 01:04:49,779
The mirror.

581
01:05:06,774 --> 01:05:08,292
We've got him.

582
01:05:08,509 --> 01:05:12,230
She's supposed to meet him at Cafe Michel, 1 p.m.

583
01:05:13,848 --> 01:05:15,537
Well, let's make sure she does.

584
01:06:12,473 --> 01:06:14,997
I'm here to meet someone.
Michael Jennings.

585
01:06:14,999 --> 01:06:16,860
- Have a seat.
- Thanks.

586
01:06:19,613 --> 01:06:22,474
Sit at that table right there.

587
01:06:23,150 --> 01:06:25,835
In the seat, with your back to the window.

588
01:06:46,407 --> 01:06:49,268
Michael, thank God you're all right.

589
01:06:49,476 --> 01:06:52,571
I thought I was never gonna see you again.

590
01:06:56,383 --> 01:06:57,810
Michael, it's me.

591
01:07:00,387 --> 01:07:02,008
Rachel.

592
01:07:04,558 --> 01:07:06,008
Look...

593
01:07:06,327 --> 01:07:08,312
You can't remember me.

594
01:07:11,131 --> 01:07:13,851
No. I'm sorry.

595
01:07:21,141 --> 01:07:26,102
Cops. We can't go in.
I'll have to wait for a clear shot.

596
01:07:26,113 --> 01:07:28,064
Maya, stall for time.

597
01:07:28,282 --> 01:07:30,842
Tell him you thought he'd remember something.

598
01:07:30,851 --> 01:07:33,109
That you two were engaged.

599
01:07:35,956 --> 01:07:38,778
I guess I thought you'd remember something.

600
01:07:38,792 --> 01:07:41,516
We've been together for three years.

601
01:07:42,196 --> 01:07:43,987
I don't know what to say.

602
01:07:45,366 --> 01:07:46,888
I'm really sorry.

603
01:07:47,701 --> 01:07:49,128
I'm trying.

604
01:07:51,939 --> 01:07:54,697
That's how he's doing this.

605
01:07:59,013 --> 01:08:03,803
Listen to me very carefully, Maya.
This is what I want you to say.

606
01:08:03,817 --> 01:08:08,346
Michael, I can see you still have the envelope.

607
01:08:08,355 --> 01:08:10,010
That means it's working.

608
01:08:10,224 --> 01:08:12,978
I know you switched the personal items.
I helped.

609
01:08:12,993 --> 01:08:16,597
- You left me a note on a mirror.
- You left me a note on a mirror.

610
01:08:16,601 --> 01:08:18,589
- I'm supposed to take something from you.
- I'm supposed to take something.

611
01:08:18,800 --> 01:08:22,003
- Something I can use to get to Stevens.
- Something I can use to get to Stevens.

612
01:08:22,069 --> 01:08:25,630
- He's a man you worked with. He's trying to fix the machine.
- He's a man you worked with.

613
01:08:25,639 --> 01:08:28,227
He's trying to fix the machine.

614
01:08:32,112 --> 01:08:34,033
Work backwards, Michael.

615
01:08:41,255 --> 01:08:43,149
Yeah. Take the swipe card.

616
01:08:43,824 --> 01:08:45,945
That's the swipe card for the campus.

617
01:08:46,160 --> 01:08:48,452
You're supposed to give that to me.

618
01:08:49,596 --> 01:08:52,987
Rachel wouldn't be hurt if he hesitated,
she'd be impatient.

619
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:58,624
Look, Michael, if you can't trust me right now,
then we are lost. For good.

620
01:08:58,605 --> 01:09:00,430
Nice.

621
01:09:00,708 --> 01:09:02,260
OK.

622
01:09:05,713 --> 01:09:08,107
I'd better get back.

623
01:09:08,882 --> 01:09:11,174
They'll get suspicious soon.

624
01:09:14,154 --> 01:09:17,675
Wait here.
I'll be back in half an hour.

625
01:09:22,363 --> 01:09:26,523
And don't worry, we end up together.

626
01:09:37,644 --> 01:09:43,544
Michael I love you.

627
01:09:59,433 --> 01:10:02,187
- What's my favorite baseball team?
- What?

628
01:10:03,537 --> 01:10:05,894
What's my favorite baseball team?

629
01:10:08,475 --> 01:10:10,426
Who cares?

630
01:10:22,689 --> 01:10:24,981
That would be the Red Sox.

631
01:10:25,982 --> 01:10:26,982
Yeah.

632
01:10:33,967 --> 01:10:37,021
- I think maybe we should go.
- Wait!

633
01:10:46,146 --> 01:10:48,734
Now we can leave.
Come on.

634
01:11:02,596 --> 01:11:04,717
Wait! Hold on.

635
01:11:04,932 --> 01:11:06,359
- You have a car?
- I might.

636
01:11:06,367 --> 01:11:08,188
You might?

637
01:11:10,037 --> 01:11:11,862
Look for a BMW!

638
01:11:12,139 --> 01:11:14,226
You gotta be joking.

639
01:11:21,182 --> 01:11:23,372
Shit! Shit!

640
01:11:24,351 --> 01:11:26,802
- Let me see that key.
- Why?

641
01:11:27,021 --> 01:11:28,676
You're in the wrong section.

642
01:11:29,990 --> 01:11:32,784
Jennings bought the BMW from Southgate Auto on the Internet.

643
01:11:32,793 --> 01:11:35,085
He had the key mailed to him four weeks ago.

644
01:11:35,096 --> 01:11:38,225
- What's the color of his car?
- It isn't a car.

645
01:12:06,560 --> 01:12:10,087
They just turned on Pine.
Intercept them on Sixth.

646
01:12:20,708 --> 01:12:24,567
- How good am I on this thing?
- You're OK!

647
01:12:32,486 --> 01:12:37,313
- Look, I just said you're OK, OK?
- OK.

648
01:13:10,291 --> 01:13:11,650
Hang on!

649
01:13:47,928 --> 01:13:52,320
- Report of shots. Southgate BMW.
- Got it.

650
01:14:23,130 --> 01:14:25,881
- Stop! I lost the envelope!
- What?

651
01:14:28,669 --> 01:14:31,530
- I'll come back and get you.
- See you!

652
01:15:52,519 --> 01:15:54,037
Got it!

653
01:16:05,232 --> 01:16:07,183
Let's get out of here.

654
01:16:11,972 --> 01:16:13,763
Take us down!

655
01:16:13,974 --> 01:16:17,797
Mike, we can help you!
We know what's going on!

656
01:16:17,811 --> 01:16:20,467
Let us bring you in!

657
01:16:32,726 --> 01:16:35,819
He's headed for the tunnel!
Cut him off! Cut him off!

658
01:17:00,621 --> 01:17:02,310
Duck!

659
01:17:05,559 --> 01:17:07,043
Split!

660
01:17:32,119 --> 01:17:33,910
You think Jennings foresaw that?

661
01:17:34,121 --> 01:17:37,375
Maybe next time he'll see a nice quiet stakeout.

662
01:18:08,489 --> 01:18:10,974
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

663
01:18:14,962 --> 01:18:16,583
It's OK.

664
01:18:16,797 --> 01:18:18,850
It's all for you anyway.

665
01:18:20,735 --> 01:18:24,660
And I -- I brought you some clothes.

666
01:18:25,406 --> 01:18:28,592
I thought you might need them.
I hope it's OK.

667
01:18:28,976 --> 01:18:30,528
Thank you.

668
01:18:31,946 --> 01:18:33,703
These are mine?

669
01:18:35,750 --> 01:18:37,644
You don't remember?

670
01:18:37,885 --> 01:18:39,335
No.

671
01:18:47,361 --> 01:18:49,948
You don't remember me, do you?

672
01:18:51,132 --> 01:18:52,582
Well...

673
01:18:59,807 --> 01:19:01,325
These are for you.

674
01:19:45,586 --> 01:19:51,542
Happy birthday to you

675
01:19:51,993 --> 01:19:56,987
- Happy birthday to you.
- You're so sweet.

676
01:20:16,050 --> 01:20:17,500
I'm sorry.

677
01:20:19,020 --> 01:20:20,470
I'm sorry.

678
01:20:21,822 --> 01:20:25,884
I just don't remember.
I shouldn't have left.

679
01:20:42,543 --> 01:20:46,461
So you're saying he sent himself
a different set of personal items...

680
01:20:46,470 --> 01:20:50,057
...ones he'd selected after using the machine
and nothing our security would flag?

681
01:20:50,067 --> 01:20:54,136
Everyday things combined with the power of foresight...

682
01:20:54,321 --> 01:20:58,281
...transform Michael from engineer to escape artist.

683
01:21:00,494 --> 01:21:03,851
I don't know about you, but I'd like to return the favor.

684
01:21:25,720 --> 01:21:28,872
Michael, are you OK?

685
01:21:33,260 --> 01:21:34,744
I'm all right.

686
01:21:37,264 --> 01:21:40,693
Michael, I don't know what you saw in your machine,...

687
01:21:40,701 --> 01:21:45,521
...but I remember, a few weeks ago,
you came back from your lab and you are pale.

688
01:21:45,539 --> 01:21:48,195
You asked me the strangest question.

689
01:21:49,610 --> 01:21:53,003
- What?
- If I knew it wouldn't work out...

690
01:21:53,013 --> 01:21:57,467
...for you and I, before we were together,
would I have done it?

691
01:21:59,787 --> 01:22:01,544
What did you say?

692
01:22:02,289 --> 01:22:05,213
That I wouldn't trade our time for anything.

693
01:22:05,926 --> 01:22:09,385
That's all we are, the sum of our experiences.

694
01:22:09,630 --> 01:22:15,480
Besides, some of the best things in life are total mistakes.

695
01:22:24,178 --> 01:22:30,140
- What?
- You know, when I checked this envelope out of Reddy Grant,...

696
01:22:30,151 --> 01:22:34,304
...they told me I signed in 20 items, but there are only 19.

697
01:22:34,488 --> 01:22:36,575
I don't understand.

698
01:23:28,542 --> 01:23:30,265
What are these pictures of?

699
01:23:44,024 --> 01:23:47,210
Michael, look at the rest of the pictures.

700
01:24:11,485 --> 01:24:13,675
Look at the last one.

701
01:24:19,793 --> 01:24:22,881
Oh, my God. It's the future.

702
01:24:24,298 --> 01:24:28,491
The machine predicts a war, and we go to war to avert it.

703
01:24:28,702 --> 01:24:34,061
It predicts a plague.
We herd all the sick together, create a plague.

704
01:24:34,074 --> 01:24:38,097
Whatever future this predicts, we make happen.

705
01:24:38,946 --> 01:24:41,768
We give over control of our lives completely.

706
01:24:43,384 --> 01:24:45,278
I did this.

707
01:24:45,653 --> 01:24:48,113
Seeing the future will destroy us.

708
01:24:59,967 --> 01:25:04,225
If you show someone their future, they have no future.

709
01:25:05,973 --> 01:25:09,432
If you take away the mystery, you take away hope.

710
01:25:12,212 --> 01:25:15,102
I have to go back.
I have to destroy that machine.

711
01:25:15,115 --> 01:25:18,278
It's impossible. The campus is huge.
There are hundreds of guards.

712
01:25:18,287 --> 01:25:24,849
Hey, I would not have given up the three years we had
together unless I was absolutely sure I could get us 50 more.

713
01:25:25,059 --> 01:25:27,879
Okay. So how do we get in?

714
01:25:29,163 --> 01:25:32,319
- We don't.
- You said everything was happening...

715
01:25:32,332 --> 01:25:35,923
...for a reason, and that includes me being here.

716
01:25:35,936 --> 01:25:37,488
So come on.

717
01:25:37,705 --> 01:25:39,999
Hey, Rachel.

718
01:25:50,518 --> 01:25:54,141
Another day at the most.
I don't have many more places to look.

719
01:25:54,321 --> 01:25:57,314
I guess you weren't as smart as you thought, Stevens.

720
01:25:57,324 --> 01:26:01,318
Hey, Jennings wouldn't find it any
faster unless he knew where to look.

721
01:26:05,900 --> 01:26:08,693
We've got the feeds from mass transit.

722
01:26:10,104 --> 01:26:12,297
He could be anywhere by now.

723
01:26:12,307 --> 01:26:16,498
Except he's not running away.
He could've given himself a way...

724
01:26:16,500 --> 01:26:19,303
...to disappear,
but look what he gave himself instead.

725
01:26:19,313 --> 01:26:22,436
His Allcom security pass.

726
01:26:22,650 --> 01:26:24,675
He's going back.

727
01:26:34,028 --> 01:26:37,655
Let's get a warrant to tap phone and data lines coming out of Allcom.

728
01:26:37,666 --> 01:26:41,752
Put some bodies on that campus.
I want that machine!

729
01:27:02,256 --> 01:27:06,352
Jennings and the girl were spotted.
What do you want me to do?

730
01:27:06,394 --> 01:27:07,844
Nothing.

731
01:27:32,586 --> 01:27:35,214
- Stay where you are.
- Nobody gets through!

732
01:27:35,222 --> 01:27:37,373
- Sir!
- I didn't do anything!

733
01:27:37,992 --> 01:27:39,214
Settle down!

734
01:27:39,860 --> 01:27:44,923
All the metal detectors on level four
just went off at the same time. Ball bearings.

735
01:27:55,042 --> 01:27:58,103
Just down the hall from the metal detectors.

736
01:28:00,181 --> 01:28:04,675
Pull the guards off the Jennings lab.
Let him slip in, think he's fooled us.

737
01:28:05,119 --> 01:28:07,270
Once he's fixed the machine, take him.

738
01:28:24,605 --> 01:28:26,362
I built this.

739
01:28:27,007 --> 01:28:30,603
This door shouldn't be open.
There's something wrong.

740
01:28:36,617 --> 01:28:38,135
They're expecting us.

741
01:28:38,352 --> 01:28:42,544
Let me close this door behind us.
And keep it shut.

742
01:28:42,757 --> 01:28:45,345
- He's in.
- Confirmed. He's in.

743
01:28:45,559 --> 01:28:48,711
Great. Once we confirm he's at the machine, let's go in after him.

744
01:28:48,729 --> 01:28:51,483
I thought we were gonna wait for him to come out.

745
01:28:51,499 --> 01:28:54,333
I can't wait! Whether it's Jennings or the machine,...

746
01:28:54,335 --> 01:28:56,629
...I don't care, as long as I get one of them.
Let's go!

747
01:29:05,112 --> 01:29:07,399
This will do. Watch out.

748
01:29:07,414 --> 01:29:10,142
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. Wait, wait. What are you doing?
- Smashing the lock.

749
01:29:10,150 --> 01:29:11,773
Hold on a second.

750
01:29:11,986 --> 01:29:15,843
You can't just smash the thing.
They'll still be able to get in.

751
01:29:16,757 --> 01:29:19,550
We gotta jam the outside reader.

752
01:29:36,610 --> 01:29:38,060
Let's go.

753
01:29:38,913 --> 01:29:43,009
Let's take a look at the future before we destroy this thing.

754
01:30:41,175 --> 01:30:44,700
I bugged it.
I rigged it so Jimmy wouldn't use it against me.

755
01:30:44,702 --> 01:30:46,699
Then you can fix it, right?

756
01:30:53,921 --> 01:30:56,345
Now, where would I have planted that bug?

757
01:30:59,760 --> 01:31:02,348
Maybe on one of the motherboards.

758
01:31:02,563 --> 01:31:06,284
Whoa, whoa, whoa, we won't be needing this, OK?

759
01:31:07,568 --> 01:31:09,325
You're dangerous with that thing.

760
01:31:09,536 --> 01:31:11,695
You must have given yourself something to help you find it.

761
01:31:11,697 --> 01:31:16,293
I don't know, what it would be.
The only things left are the bullet and, uh, this.

762
01:31:16,300 --> 01:31:18,570
- A crossword?
- Yeah.

763
01:31:22,216 --> 01:31:23,905
Look at this.

764
01:31:24,184 --> 01:31:25,975
Twelve down.

765
01:31:27,221 --> 01:31:29,342
Maybe it's here.

766
01:31:35,429 --> 01:31:37,755
Nine, ten, eleven, twelve.

767
01:31:40,501 --> 01:31:42,053
Let's take a look.

768
01:31:42,736 --> 01:31:44,994
Maybe it's a circuit diagram.

769
01:31:47,508 --> 01:31:50,034
I wouldn't have put it in the primary path.

770
01:31:53,580 --> 01:31:55,269
Twelve down.

771
01:32:12,566 --> 01:32:13,823
Take him.

772
01:32:14,034 --> 01:32:19,592
OK, corridor three, sublevel A, Jennings' lab.

773
01:32:28,482 --> 01:32:33,841
All right, let's put this thing to good use one last time.

774
01:32:33,854 --> 01:32:35,805
Let's get us out of here.

775
01:33:23,103 --> 01:33:24,360
That's in the lab.

776
01:33:26,340 --> 01:33:28,325
It's the catwalk.

777
01:33:47,695 --> 01:33:53,316
Look, I've changed my future before using this thing.
I can do it again.

778
01:34:12,553 --> 01:34:15,705
We don't have any more time.
We got to destroy this before they get to it.

779
01:34:16,190 --> 01:34:18,910
Reprogram the door to Jennings' lab, please.

780
01:34:18,926 --> 01:34:20,376
Now.

781
01:34:26,400 --> 01:34:29,529
He must've done something to the controller.

782
01:34:30,504 --> 01:34:33,633
- How are we gonna get out of here Micheal?
- I don't know.

783
01:35:05,105 --> 01:35:06,396
Clear!

784
01:35:06,907 --> 01:35:09,729
- What are you doing?
- These things are liquid hydrogen.

785
01:35:09,843 --> 01:35:12,870
They're used to cool the machine.
They fire in order.

786
01:35:12,880 --> 01:35:14,330
Number one just fired.

787
01:35:14,548 --> 01:35:18,466
When it gets down to number six here,
that's all she wrote.

788
01:35:19,586 --> 01:35:21,980
I'll see you when this goes off, Jimmy.

789
01:35:27,928 --> 01:35:29,219
Come on!

790
01:35:34,568 --> 01:35:36,928
You see?
You judge too soon.

791
01:35:54,788 --> 01:35:57,883
They went out through the vent.
Spread out, find them.

792
01:36:27,621 --> 01:36:29,173
Position three standing by.

793
01:36:30,758 --> 01:36:32,349
Come on.

794
01:36:34,395 --> 01:36:36,016
Freeze!

795
01:36:44,205 --> 01:36:45,427
Look out.

796
01:36:48,575 --> 01:36:50,162
Seal off all exits to the lab.

797
01:37:08,896 --> 01:37:14,790
All right, Jennings, let's see what you've been up to.

798
01:37:29,483 --> 01:37:33,402
Rachel, go for the door, OK?

799
01:38:59,273 --> 01:39:01,064
Drop the gun.

800
01:39:04,912 --> 01:39:06,569
Drop the gun.

801
01:39:59,233 --> 01:40:02,453
Looks like Michael's got a date on the catwalks.

802
01:40:07,475 --> 01:40:09,663
Let's make sure he makes it.

803
01:41:28,055 --> 01:41:29,879
- Let's go.
- No. We can't take the catwalk.

804
01:41:29,891 --> 01:41:33,119
I know. We won't, I promise.
Come on, let's go.

805
01:41:43,737 --> 01:41:47,194
- Michael! What are you doing?
- Rachel, go. Go. I'll distract them.

806
01:41:47,197 --> 01:41:48,529
- Go, please.
- No!

807
01:41:48,532 --> 01:41:51,830
Listen to me. This is my debt.
I built this machine.

808
01:41:51,845 --> 01:41:54,630
- I have to pay for it.
- No! You come with me now!

809
01:41:54,638 --> 01:41:57,204
You promised you'd change your fate!

810
01:41:57,217 --> 01:41:59,270
Please, we don't have time.

811
01:41:59,486 --> 01:42:05,414
If you love me, if you care about me. Go.
Have a good life.

812
01:42:07,594 --> 01:42:09,749
Remember me.

813
01:42:11,865 --> 01:42:13,520
Damn you.

814
01:42:19,507 --> 01:42:21,332
Jimmy.

815
01:42:21,776 --> 01:42:26,840
You want to kill me, come do it yourself.

816
01:42:31,485 --> 01:42:35,404
Here I am. You want me?
Come get me.

817
01:42:40,628 --> 01:42:43,421
- Hi, Jimmy.
- Hi, Mike.

818
01:42:44,899 --> 01:42:47,391
- Looks like this is it, huh?
- Yeah, it is, Mike.

819
01:42:47,401 --> 01:42:50,553
- You only have yourself to blame.
- That's a lie.

820
01:42:50,571 --> 01:42:53,632
You can't change your fate, Mike.
You're gonna die today.

821
01:42:54,875 --> 01:42:56,393
Maybe.

822
01:42:57,478 --> 01:43:00,202
But you're not going to kill me.

823
01:43:06,320 --> 01:43:09,877
That's right, Mike.
I've seen the future.

824
01:44:25,399 --> 01:44:28,551
Still think you can change your fate, Mike?

825
01:44:30,304 --> 01:44:32,289
I am the future, Mike!

826
01:44:58,565 --> 01:45:01,055
- Rethrick has Jennings.
- Retire him.

827
01:45:01,068 --> 01:45:03,101
- What?
- We have the machine.

828
01:45:03,103 --> 01:45:07,432
We can't risk its creator falling into the wrong hands.
Come on.

829
01:46:06,367 --> 01:46:08,386
Don't blame me.

830
01:46:09,336 --> 01:46:13,023
You and Michael would've lived happily ever after, no memory wipe.

831
01:46:13,040 --> 01:46:15,366
He's the one who saw something he didn't like.

832
01:46:15,576 --> 01:46:19,172
He's the one who decided he wanted to stop the program.

833
01:46:35,429 --> 01:46:39,025
Look at it this way, you did change the future, Michael.

834
01:46:39,033 --> 01:46:41,793
Before you interfered you both would've lived...

835
01:46:41,802 --> 01:46:45,830
...we would still be friends, instead of ending up like this.

836
01:46:46,273 --> 01:46:48,724
It wasn't meant to be.

837
01:46:54,948 --> 01:46:57,172
Giving up so easy?

838
01:46:59,286 --> 01:47:03,342
Don't you believe in second chances?

839
01:47:04,158 --> 01:47:07,481
To tell you the truth, I do.

840
01:47:19,573 --> 01:47:21,831
Go, go, go.

841
01:48:00,180 --> 01:48:01,774
Rachel!

842
01:49:02,342 --> 01:49:04,202
Let's go.

843
01:49:09,416 --> 01:49:11,344
Look.

844
01:49:20,928 --> 01:49:23,049
Any records? Any papers?

845
01:49:23,264 --> 01:49:26,125
Explosion destroyed everything.

846
01:49:31,939 --> 01:49:36,229
- Are we trying to salvage that or what?
- I guess we don't get the machine, do we?

847
01:50:03,871 --> 01:50:06,026
Any sign of Jennings?

848
01:50:06,774 --> 01:50:10,534
No, I'm afraid he didn't make it.

849
01:50:54,288 --> 01:50:59,876
What was Shorty thinking, starting a nursery?
I mean, these plants are on life-support.

850
01:50:59,927 --> 01:51:02,850
What do you mean? Really?
He told me he had a green thumb.

851
01:51:02,863 --> 01:51:05,457
Gangrene is more like it.

852
01:51:05,466 --> 01:51:09,025
Lucky for Shorty, I'm a biologist.

853
01:51:09,036 --> 01:51:12,087
Lucky for both of us, since I failed biology,...

854
01:51:12,095 --> 01:51:15,223
- ...I'm no help to either one of you.
- So you say.

855
01:51:15,242 --> 01:51:19,003
Too bad, though, because I'm looking for a partner...

856
01:51:19,013 --> 01:51:22,035
- ...for a start-up company.
- Really? Doing what?

857
01:51:22,082 --> 01:51:24,176
We're gonna save the world.

858
01:51:26,721 --> 01:51:28,581
I don't think I'm your guy.

859
01:51:28,789 --> 01:51:32,781
But would you settle for someone who wants to help you change it?

860
01:51:32,784 --> 01:51:35,720
- Mmm, okay.
- Good.

861
01:51:35,730 --> 01:51:40,021
So how does it end for us, Michael?
I mean, what's in our future?

862
01:51:40,067 --> 01:51:45,326
You know, I don't know.
I kind of like it that way.

863
01:51:45,339 --> 01:51:48,293
- I do know one thing.
- What's that?

864
01:51:48,375 --> 01:51:52,494
I never want to forget anything ever again.

865
01:51:55,149 --> 01:51:59,905
Break it up, break it up.
The birdman cometh.

866
01:52:01,222 --> 01:52:02,949
- Shorty.
- It's dinner.

867
01:52:02,957 --> 01:52:05,214
- You found them.
- Yes, I did.

868
01:52:05,225 --> 01:52:07,676
- Who does everything for everybody around here?
- You do.

869
01:52:07,695 --> 01:52:09,486
- You're right.
- You're my hero.

870
01:52:09,496 --> 01:52:11,215
Thank you very much.

871
01:52:11,232 --> 01:52:14,225
- You hear that? I'm a hero.
- That's great.

872
01:52:15,236 --> 01:52:17,528
I think I remember.
Are those our birds?

873
01:52:17,738 --> 01:52:20,731
Yes, of course they are.
We bought them together.

874
01:52:20,741 --> 01:52:24,907
You remember the birds?
Well done. You could see into the future...

875
01:52:24,912 --> 01:52:27,868
...and all you remember are Polly and Tweety over there.

876
01:52:27,881 --> 01:52:31,309
- Why don't you remember something that would make us rich, huh, Mike?
- Wait a second.

877
01:52:31,317 --> 01:52:32,438
What is it?

878
01:52:32,553 --> 01:52:35,541
- I think there was something else.
- No, no, no.

879
01:52:35,556 --> 01:52:38,510
The envelope's empty.
Don't worry about it.

880
01:52:38,515 --> 01:52:42,488
Hold on. I'm working backward here.

881
01:52:46,534 --> 01:52:52,690
"If you only look where you can't go,
you will miss the riches below."

882
01:52:55,042 --> 01:52:58,096
I must've known you'd never get rid of these birds.
Alright?

883
01:52:58,102 --> 01:52:59,865
Of course not. They're family.

884
01:53:00,080 --> 01:53:05,041
So I knew this would be here.
What only looks where it can't go?

885
01:53:05,052 --> 01:53:06,775
A caged bird.

886
01:53:08,722 --> 01:53:11,515
"You will miss the riches below."

887
01:53:14,895 --> 01:53:17,016
The riches below.

888
01:53:25,373 --> 01:53:27,498
What is that?

889
01:53:27,708 --> 01:53:31,497
Well, that's a $90-million lottery ticket.

890
01:53:31,512 --> 01:53:34,002
- Wait. Wait a minute.
- It's $90 million.

891
01:53:34,014 --> 01:53:36,145
- Nice.
- Yes, I'm proud of it.

892
01:53:36,149 --> 01:53:38,377
Wait a minute. No.

893
01:53:38,385 --> 01:53:40,618
- Wait a-- Hold on.
- What are you doing?

894
01:53:40,621 --> 01:53:41,543
You know what?

895
01:53:41,755 --> 01:53:45,214
I think now's probably a good time to discuss my commission, 33%.

896
01:53:45,226 --> 01:53:47,455
- I thought it was 5.
- No, 33%.

897
01:53:47,461 --> 01:53:51,318
- Thirty-three percent! We had a deal at five percent.
- He deserves it. - Absolutely.

898
01:53:51,332 --> 01:53:57,283
- It was found on-- It was found on my premises.
- You know what? I'll come back. I'm going to cash this in.

